      {
        "id": 66041,
        "name": "link ‚ú¶",
        "username": "awaitlink",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/awaitlink/{size}/48975_2.png",
        "created_at": "2020-05-26T15:23:31.243Z",
        "cooked": "<p>There are already two different styles of the Desktop app (that depend on the master device): Android and iOS. AFAIK they only affect message bubble coloring at the moment. I imagine it would make sense to change the emoji font based on that instead of providing an extra option.</p>\n<p>However, there‚Äôs no such thing as</p>\n<aside class=\"quote group-volunteer_moderators quote-modified\" data-username=\"Salt505\" data-post=\"1\" data-topic=\"14477\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img loading=\"lazy\" alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://community.signalusers.org/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/salt505/48/8288_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"> Salt:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Android - matches the style of emoji found on the latest version of Android</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>Simply because different vendors have different emojis. You could use <a href=\"https://emojipedia.org/google/\">Google‚Äôs emojis</a>, which I quote:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>are used on most Android devices</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>However that still wouldn‚Äôt satisfy everyone I think.</p>\n<aside class=\"quote group-volunteer_moderators quote-modified\" data-username=\"Salt505\" data-post=\"1\" data-topic=\"14477\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img loading=\"lazy\" alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://community.signalusers.org/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/salt505/48/8288_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"> Salt:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>System - respects the default system emoji found on whatever device is being used (MacOS/Windows)</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>Linux has to be taken into account as well. At the very least this ‚Äúsystem‚Äù option shouldn‚Äôt be the default IMO, as that can lead to confused users (see point 2 below).</p>\n<hr>\n<p>Additionally, I believe it‚Äôs still better to have one consistent emoji set on all platforms (currently that happens to be Apple‚Äôs set; only Signal Android allows optionally using the system set at the moment), because:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>different emoji sets sometimes assign different meaning to the same emoji;</li>\n<li>not all devices supported by Signal support newest emojis but Signal Android can remedy that by using the built-in set.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>In fact I think these are exactly the reasons why Signal uses the built-in set by default (see <a href=\"https://support.signal.org/hc/en-us/articles/360017561992\">this support article</a>):</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Signal Android includes built-in emoji functionality for consistency between platforms and to support older Android devices whose set of emoji may be outdated or incomplete.</p>\n</blockquote>",
