        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/awaitlink/{size}/48975_2.png",
        "created_at": "2020-05-26T15:31:31.642Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote group-volunteer_moderators\" data-username=\"Salt505\" data-post=\"3\" data-topic=\"14477\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img loading=\"lazy\" alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://community.signalusers.org/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/salt505/48/8288_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"> Salt:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>maybe that option could be hidden on Linux.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>No, I think if such an option is given it should be absolutely present in Linux. You can install any font you want. However, depending on the distro, an emoji set might not be pre-installed, so I think this shouldn‚Äôt be used by default.</p>",
