        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote group-volunteer_moderators\" data-username=\"awaitlink\" data-post=\"4\" data-topic=\"14477\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img loading=\"lazy\" alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://community.signalusers.org/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/awaitlink/48/48975_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"> awaitlink:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>However, depending on the distro, an emoji set might not be pre-installed, so I think this shouldn‚Äôt be used by default.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>Ah ok, I see. My bad, I‚Äôm not at all familiar with Linux.</p>\n<aside class=\"quote group-volunteer_moderators\" data-username=\"awaitlink\" data-post=\"2\" data-topic=\"14477\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img loading=\"lazy\" alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://community.signalusers.org/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/awaitlink/48/48975_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"> awaitlink:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>not all devices supported by Signal support newest emojis but Signal Android can remedy that by using the built-in set.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>Yes, any devices that don‚Äôt support <em>all</em> of the emojis could be forced to use the ones included in Signal by default.</p>",
