        "created_at": "2021-09-30T01:51:42.425Z",
        "cooked": "<p>I‚Äôm coming here to voice support for this as well, as I had commented on an issue on GitHub from 2016(!), but it was locked and now just closed.</p>\n<aside class=\"onebox githubissue\" data-onebox-src=\"https://github.com/signalapp/Signal-Desktop/issues/975\">\n  <header class=\"source\">\n\n      <a href=\"https://github.com/signalapp/Signal-Desktop/issues/975\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\">github.com/signalapp/Signal-Desktop</a>\n  </header>\n\n  <article class=\"onebox-body\">\n    <div class=\"github-row\">\n  <div class=\"github-icon-container\" title=\"Issue\">\n\t  <svg width=\"60\" height=\"60\" class=\"github-icon\" viewbox=\"0 0 14 16\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M7 2.3c3.14 0 5.7 2.56 5.7 5.7s-2.56 5.7-5.7 5.7A5.71 5.71 0 0 1 1.3 8c0-3.14 2.56-5.7 5.7-5.7zM7 1C3.14 1 0 4.14 0 8s3.14 7 7 7 7-3.14 7-7-3.14-7-7-7zm1 3H6v5h2V4zm0 6H6v2h2v-2z\"></path></svg>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"github-info-container\">\n    <h4>\n      <a href=\"https://github.com/signalapp/Signal-Desktop/issues/975\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\">Request: Allow choice of Google/Android emoji's, like the Android app</a>\n    </h4>\n\n    <div class=\"github-info\">\n      <div class=\"date\">\n        opened <span class=\"discourse-local-date\" data-format=\"ll\" data-date=\"2016-11-18\" data-time=\"05:12:29\" data-timezone=\"UTC\">05:12AM - 18 Nov 16 UTC</span>\n      </div>\n\n        <div class=\"date\">\n          closed <span class=\"discourse-local-date\" data-format=\"ll\" data-date=\"2021-09-29\" data-time=\"22:30:24\" data-timezone=\"UTC\">10:30PM - 29 Sep 21 UTC</span>\n        </div>\n\n      <div class=\"user\">\n        <a href=\"https://github.com/lucasjsmith\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\">\n          <img alt=\"lucasjsmith\" src=\"https://community.signalusers.org/uploads/db3609/original/3X/0/f/0f40b1f0e0e047304977aa163ba1994446cf6c56.jpeg\" class=\"onebox-avatar-inline\" width=\"20\" height=\"20\">\n          lucasjsmith\n        </a>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n\n    <div class=\"labels\">\n        <span style=\"display:inline-block;margin-top:2px;background-color: #B8B8B8;padding: 2px;border-radius: 4px;color: #fff;margin-left: 3px;\">\n          Feature Request\n        </span>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n  <div class=\"github-row\">\n    <p class=\"github-body-container\">- [x] I have searched open and closed issues for duplicates\n\n-----------------<span class=\"show-more-container\"><a href=\"\" rel=\"noopener\" class=\"show-more\">‚Ä¶</a></span><span class=\"excerpt hidden\">-----------------------\n\nPlease allow a setting to use Android-styled emojis, like there is in the Android app. The Desktop app allows the use of \"Android\" styling, and it should support following that look in this respect too.</span></p>\n  </div>\n\n  </article>\n\n  <div class=\"onebox-metadata\">\n    \n    \n  </div>\n\n  <div style=\"clear: both\"></div>\n</aside>\n\n<p>To reiterate my thoughts from there, I installed the Linux app on my desktop and was surprised to see Apple emoji, when my OS includes the open source, full color <a href=\"https://github.com/googlei18n/noto-emoji\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\">Noto Emoji</a>. I was even more surprised when I went to the settings and did not see a toggle for native emoji support like there is in the Android app.</p>\n<p>Noto Emoji do an excellent job of reducing ambiguity while being more platform agnostic and fully open source. I <em>would</em> recommend Signal move to them across all platforms, but that‚Äôs understandably a different conversation for a different issue.</p>\n<p>At the very least, allowing the use of the OS‚Äôs native emoji (like the Android app does) would make sense. I could see an argument to have an option for Noto Emoji as an alternative to the Apple-style ones, but native emoji support would be acceptable as well.</p>\n<p>Regarding the ‚Äúconsistency‚Äù argument, it goes both ways. Every other app, web page, and experience on my machine shares a consistent emoji set, as it‚Äôs just a font. Signal sticks out by being the only app with completely foreign Apple-style emoji injected into my messages versus using the consistent platform emoji set. Consistency with the user‚Äôs platform is extremely important.</p>",
